06881nam a22009735i 9780231555173DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021027096  a97802315551737 a10.7312/star203662doi  a(DE-B1597)650097  a(OCoLC)1261768576  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHM479.B445 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a301.0922231 aStarr, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDefining the Age :bDaniel Bell, His Time and Ours /cPaul Starr, Julian E. Zelizer. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. OVERVIEW -- t1. Remembering Daniel Bell: Two Perspectives -- t2. Daniel Bell’s Three-Dimensional Puzzle -- tPART II. POLITICS AND IDEOLOGY -- t3. Of But Not in the Left: Daniel Bell on Radical Politics -- t4. Daniel Bell and the Radical Right -- t5. The End of Ideology, the Long Nineties, and the History of the Present -- tPART III. THE POST-INDUSTRIAL TRANSFORMATION -- t6. “Post-Industrial” Versus “Neoliberal”: Rival Definitions of Our Age -- t7. Assessing Daniel Bell in the Age of Big Tech -- t8. The Post-Industrial University as We Know It: Daniel Bell’s Vision, Today’s Realities -- t9. Daniel Bell, Social Forecaster -- tPART IV. CAPITALISM, CULTURE, AND THE PUBLIC HOUSEHOLD -- t10. The Cultural Contradictions of Capitalism, Then and Now -- t11. The Double Bind: Daniel Bell, the Public Household, and Financialization -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe sociologist Daniel Bell was an uncommonly acute observer of the structural forces transforming the United States and other advanced societies in the twentieth century. The titles of Bell’s major books—The End of Ideology (1960), The Coming of Post-Industrial Society (1973), and The Cultural Contradictions of Capitalism (1976)—became hotly debated frameworks for understanding the era when they were published. In Defining the Age, Paul Starr and Julian E. Zelizer bring together a group of distinguished contributors to consider how well Bell’s ideas captured their historical moment and continue to provide profound insights into today’s world. Wide-ranging essays demonstrate how Bell’s writing has informed thinking about subjects such as the history of socialism, the roots of the radical right, the emerging postindustrial society, and the role of the university. The book also examines Bell’s intellectual trajectory and distinctive political stance. Calling himself “a socialist in economics, a liberal in politics, and a conservative in culture,” he resisted being pigeon-holed, especially as a neoconservative.Defining the Age features essays from historians Jenny Andersson, David A. Bell, Michael Kazin, and Margaret O’Mara; sociologist Steven Brint; media scholar Fred Turner; and political theorists Jan-Werner Müller and Stefan Eich. While differing in their judgments, they agree on one premise: Bell’s ideas deserve the kind of nuanced and serious attention that they finally receive in this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSocial scienceszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSociologistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aSociologyzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aThe Coming of Post-Industrial Society.  aThe Cultural Contradictions of Capitalism.  aThe End of Ideology.  afascism.  aliberalism.  aradical right.  asocialism.1 aAndersson, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v